Title: Linking forum posts - GlobalWarming-01-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Medieval time warming & geologic & historical time sea level rise -- what do models say?
Input.posts:
Not sure where this question goes. We heard in wk 6 that medieval times had a .5 C degree temperature rise over the course of what looks to be AD 800 to AD 1150 from the lecture graph -- see hockey stick lecture. In wk 7 we are doing a homework of short vs long term sea level change and lectures on ice sheet melting and sea level rise. So, the question 4,5 in the short vs long term sea level change assignment gave a formula for geologic time sea level rise per change in temperature. The q4 is a significant value and the medieval time warming is likewise a significt degree C change. So the natural question is --- Has there been and is there continuing to be a sea level rise from the medieval time warming?? Or was the 350 years here too short and somewhat canceled by the later little ice age. What do the models say about medieval time and little ice time temp changes and resultant sea levels?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Bord, Did you do Number Cruncher #3? There are some similarities between concepts in that exercise and sea level changes. Question 4 in the Short vs Long Term Sea Level assignment has you calculate sea levels that will eventually be achieved on geologic timescales. This is kind of like the equilibrium temperature in NC3. But, like the transient temperature in NC3, the sea level takes time to reach this equilibrium - it probably relaxes toward it with some time constant, probably on the order of thousands of years (I'm just guessing on this number). So, there probably was a blip in sea level during to the medieval warming period. How big, I don't know - that depends on the time constant. It definitely wouldn't be as big as what you calculate from Q4. And, I don't think sea level continued to rise after the warming period ended. As you speculated, it probably dropped during the Little Ice Age.

Input.threadtitle: Week 5 Quiz - CO2 Dissolved in Oceans
Input.posts:
I am puzzled by this Question. (I realise that the questions are randomised, and that not everyone may have got this question) Options: Almost none. About 10%. About half. About 75%. Almost 100%. Firstly, 'just atmosphere and ocean'. What no land vegitation either? Or just no weathering? Lecture 6.4 Perturbed CarbonCarbon Cycle (2:19) By Dr Archers numbers CO2 emissions (anthropogenic?) are 8 Gtons/yr. Oceans absorb 2. So 2/8 = 25% (not close to any answer option) Have I misinterpreted something important here? It also got me wondering about what controls the rate of absorption of CO2 at the ocean surface. I see that once the CO2 is dissolved, the buffering chemistry kicks in, but I am still unclear on what determines the rate at which CO2 transfers from atmosphere to ocean. Did I miss the point somewhere in the lecture?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Tony, The question is asking about timescales much longer than those you are considering above (see The Long CO2 Tail lecture). I realize this was a bit ambiguous in the question, so I've changed it. Thanks for noticing this. As for your second question, there are many things that determine how quickly the ocean absorbs CO2. Colder water would probably absorb it faster, as would more turbulent water. Anything that keeps the concentration of dissolved CO2 low near the surface would accelerate the rate of absorption (mixing or photosynthesis, for example). I would guess the rate of mixing is a much larger factor than the rate of photosynthesis.

I am puzzled by this Question. (I realise that the questions are randomised, and that not everyone may have got this question) Options: Almost none. About 10%. About half. About 75%. Almost 100%. Firstly, 'just atmosphere and ocean'. What no land vegitation either? Or just no weathering? Lecture 6.4 Perturbed CarbonCarbon Cycle (2:19) By Dr Archers numbers CO2 emissions (anthropogenic?) are 8 Gtons/yr. Oceans absorb 2. So 2/8 = 25% (not close to any answer option) Have I misinterpreted something important here? It also got me wondering about what controls the rate of absorption of CO2 at the ocean surface. I see that once the CO2 is dissolved, the buffering chemistry kicks in, but I am still unclear on what determines the rate at which CO2 transfers from atmosphere to ocean. Did I miss the point somewhere in the lecture?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Tony, The question is asking about timescales much longer than those you are considering above (see The Long CO2 Tail lecture). I realize this was a bit ambiguous in the question, so I've changed it. Thanks for noticing this. As for your second question, there are many things that determine how quickly the ocean absorbs CO2. Colder water would probably absorb it faster, as would more turbulent water. Anything that keeps the concentration of dissolved CO2 low near the surface would accelerate the rate of absorption (mixing or photosynthesis, for example). I would guess the rate of mixing is a much larger factor than the rate of photosynthesis.

Title: Linking forum posts - GlobalWarming-01-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
I have a question on the Peak Oil concept in the week 4 lectures. He gives 2 models, one that has a rate of production vs a rate of formation, and one with a Gaussian curve with Peak Oil - the latter assumes an exponential increase in the rate of oil demand. What is the case for assuming an exponential increase in demand?
Upvotes:
0
The Hubbert Curve used to predict peak oil (or other resources) is actually a derivative of the logistic curve (also S-curve or sigmoid function), not a Gaussian curve as stated in the lecture. They resemble each other in that both are bell-shaped, but the logistic function has exponential tails. The logistic function is widely used to describe bounded geometric growth. There is a great explanation and examples at this link: http://www.billharlan.com/papers/logistic/logistic.html
Upvotes:
2
Thanks for the post, but I don't see how that addresses my question of exponential demand growth. In fact it seems to support my case re: arguments for limited demand at a certain point.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Jason, I'm not entirely sure, but I think it relates to exponential population growth.
Instructor's post : Hi Jason, I'm not entirely sure, but I think it relates to exponential population growth.
Upvotes:
0

Title: Linking forum posts - GlobalWarming-01-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
The final lecture suggested that a climate sensitivity of 2C makes sense just considering CO2 radiative forcing plus the water vapor and ice-albedo feedbacks. And then on top of that, climate models generate 0-2C additional sensitivity due to clouds. I'm not sure why the sensitivity due to clouds comes out positive. I would have thought that higher levels of water vapor in the atmosphere would mean more clouds and hence, if they are stratus clouds, a cooling effect. Or is it that the temperature increase leads to lower *relative* humidities, (less saturated) even though the quantity of water is higher?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi James, I'm not sure why either. It could be that you get more cirrus clouds in a warmer climate. It could be lower relative humidities, as you suggested, it could be a different spatial distribution of clouds (i.e. the whole 'wet places get wetter, dry places drier' scenario), which might diminish the cooling effect of stratus clouds. Maybe this is why there is such a high degree of uncertainty in the component of climate sensitivity from clouds.

Title: Linking forum posts - GlobalWarming-01-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
An in-lecture quiz question in lecture 3-2 suggests that there is no coriolis force acting at the equator. I can see how there would be no coriolis force acting on N/S motions, but it seems there would be an up/down coriolis force acting on E/W motions, and an E/W coriolis force acting on up/down motions. Am I missing something here?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi James, There's no up/down coriolis force or e/w coriolis force in the northern and southern hemispheres, so those forces also don't exist at the equator. The fact that there's only a coriolis force in 1 dimension arises from the fact that Earth only has 1 n/s rotation axis.
